{"title_page": "Codex Beratinus", "text_new": "{{For|the similarly named manuscript|Codex Beratinus II}}\n{{New Testament manuscript infobox\n| form   = Uncial\n| number = '''043'''\n| image  = Page from the Codex Purpureus Beratinus.JPG\n| isize  = 220\n| caption= Left: Facsimile of Matthew 6:30b-7:2a Right: Page from Codex Beratinus\n| name   = Beratinus\n| sign   = \u03a6\n| text   = [[Gospel of Matthew]], [[Gospel of Mark]]\n| script = [[Greek language|Greek]]\n| date   = 6th-century\n| found  =\n| now at = [[National Archives of Albania]]\n| cite   = P. Batiffol, ''Evangeliorum codex Graecus purpureus Beratinus \u03a6'', (Paris and Rome, 1882)\n| size   = {{\u00d7|31|27|cm}}\n| type   = [[Byzantine text-type]]\n| cat    = V\n| hand   =\n| note   =\n}}\n\n'''Codex Purpureus Beratinus''' ({{lang-sq|Kodiku i Beratit, Kodiku i Purpurt i Beratit}}) designated by '''\u03a6''' or '''043''' (in the [[Biblical manuscript#Gregory-Aland|Gregory-Aland]] numbering), \u03b5 17 ([[Biblical manuscript#Von Soden|von Soden]]), is an [[uncial]] [[illuminated manuscript]] [[Gospel book]] written in [[Greek language|Greek]]. Dated [[Palaeography|palaeographically]] to the 6th-century, the [[manuscript]] is written in an uncial hand on [[Purple parchment|purple vellum]] with silver ink. The [[codex]] is preserved at the Albanian National Archives (Nr. 1) in [[Tirana]], [[Albania]].{{r|Aland}} It was formerly possessed by the [[Saint George|St. George]] Church in the town of [[Berat]], Albania, hence the 'Beratinus' appellation.\n\n== Description ==\nCodex Beratinus contains only the [[Gospel of Matthew]] and the [[Gospel of Mark]], with several considerable [[lacuna (manuscripts)|lacunae]] (Matthew 1:1-6:3, 7:26-8:7, 18:23-19:3, and Mark 14:62-end). The codex contains 190 extant parchment leaves measuring 31.4 \u00d7 26.8&nbsp;cm, or approximately the same size as those of [[Codex Alexandrinus]], and have two columns per page, but the letters are much larger.<ref name = Kenyon>[[Frederic G. Kenyon]], [https://archive.org/stream/handbooktotextua00kenyuoft#page/120/mode/2up ''Handbook to the Textual Criticism of the New Testament''], London2, 1912, p. 120.</ref> It is written with 17 lines per page,<ref name=Aland>{{Cite book\n | last = Aland\n | first = Kurt\n | authorlink = Kurt Aland\n | last2 = Aland\n | first2 = Barbara\n | authorlink2 = Barbara Aland\n | others = Erroll F. Rhodes (trans.)\n | title = The Text of the New Testament: An Introduction to the Critical Editions and to the Theory and Practice of Modern Textual Criticism\n | publisher = [[William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company]]\n | year = 1995\n | location = Grand Rapids\n | page = 118\n | url = \n | doi = \n | id = \n | isbn = 978-0-8028-4098-1}}</ref> 8-12 letters per line, in very regular letters, in silver ink.<ref name = Metzger>[[Bruce M. Metzger]], [[Bart D. Ehrman]], \"The Text of the New Testament: Its Transmission, Corruption and Restoration\", ''[[Oxford University Press]]'' (New York - Oxford, 2005), p. 84.</ref> The title and the first line in Mark are written in gold.<ref name = Gregory>{{Cite book | last = Gregory | first = Caspar Ren\u00e9 | authorlink = Caspar Ren\u00e9 Gregory | title = Textkritik des Neuen Testaments | publisher = J.C. Hinrichs\u2019sche Buchhandlung | year = 1900 | location = Leipzig | volume = 1 | page = 93 | url = https://archive.org/stream/textkritikdesne00greggoog#page/n105/mode/2up | isbn = }}</ref> The writing is continuous in full lines without [[stichometry]]. Quotations from the [[Old Testament]] are marked with an inverted comma (<).\n\nThe text is divided according to the {{lang|grc|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03b1}} (chapters) and according to the [[Eusebian Canons|Ammonian Sections]] (smaller than {{lang|grc|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03b1}}). On the left margin are inserted the numerals of the {{lang|grc|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03b1}} and above the pages are inserted the {{lang|grc|\u03c4\u03b9\u03c4\u03bb\u03bf\u03b9}} (titles) of the {{lang|grc|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03b1}}. The numerals of the Ammonian sections are given on the left margin, and a references to the Eusebian Canons were added by a later hand in the 8th century. A note in the manuscript states that the loss of the other two Gospels is due to \"the [[Franks]] of [[Champagne, France|Champagne]]\", i.e. some of the [[Crusades|Crusaders]], who may have seen it while at [[Patmos]], where it was believed formerly to have been.{{r|Kenyon}}\n\n== Text ==\nThe text of the codex is generally of the [[Byzantine text-type]], but it contains the long [[Western text-type|Western]] addition after Matthew 20:28, occurring also in [[Codex Bezae]]:<ref name = Metzger/> Aland gave for it the following textual profile: 131<sup>1</sup>, 83<sup>1/2</sup>, 11<sup>2</sup>, 18<sup>s</sup>.<ref name = Aland/>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"But seek to increase from that which is small, and to become less from which is greater. When you enter into a house and are summoned to dine, do not sit down at the prominent places, lest perchance a man more honorable than you come in afterwards, and he who invited you come and say to you, \"Go down lower\"; and you shall be ashamed. But if you sit down in the inferior place, and one inferior to you come in, then he that invited you will say to you, \"Go up higher\"; and this will be advantageous for you.\"<ref>Bruce M. Metzger, Bart D. Ehrman, ''The Text of the New Testament: Its Transmission, Corruption and Restoration'', [[Oxford University Press]], 2005, p. 71.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn [[Matthew 21:9]], the following interpolation occurs, sharing affinity only with [[Curetonian Gospels|syr<sup>cur</sup>]]:<ref>[[Eberhard Nestle]], [[Erwin Nestle]], Barbara Aland and [[Kurt Aland]] (eds), ''[[Novum Testamentum Graece]]'', 26th edition, (Stuttgart: ''[[Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft]]'', 1991), p. 58. [NA26]</ref>\n<blockquote>\n\u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b5\u03be\u03b5\u03bb\u03b8\u03bf\u03bd \u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c5\u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03b9\u03bd \u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03c9 \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03b9 \u03c7\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b4\u03bf\u03be\u03b1\u03b6\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03b8\u03b5\u03bf\u03bd \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9 \u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c9\u03bd \u03b5\u03b9\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n''And many went out to meet him; all who were seeing [him] round about were rejoicing and glorifying God.''\n</blockquote>\n\nIn Matthew 27:9, in the phrase \u03b5\u03c0\u03bb\u03b7\u03c1\u03c9\u03b8\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c1\u03b7\u03b8\u03b5\u03bd \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1 \u0399\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03bc\u03b9\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03b7\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 (''fulfilled what was spoken by Jeremiah the prophet'') the word \u0399\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03bc\u03b9\u03bf\u03c5 ([[Jeremiah]]) is omitted, as in [[Minuscule 33]], [[Codex Vercellensis|a]], [[Codex Veronensis|b]], [[Syriac Sinaiticus|syr<sup>s</sup>]], [[Peshitta|syr<sup>p</sup>]], and [[Coptic versions of the Bible|cop<sup>bo</sup>]].<ref name = NA81>\u039d\u039126, p. 81</ref>\n\nIn Matthew 27:16 it has additional reading \u03bf\u03c2 \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c6\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bd \u03b7\u03bd \u03b2\u03b5\u03b2\u03bb\u03b7\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c6\u03c5\u03bb\u03b1\u03ba\u03b7\u03bd (''who for murder and insurrection had been thrown in prison'').<ref name = NA81/>\n\nIn Matthew 27:35, it includes \u1f35\u03bd\u03b1 \u03c0\u03bb\u03b7\u03c1\u03ce\u03b8\u03b7 \u03c4\u1f78 \u1fe4\u03b7\u03b8\u1f72\u03bd \u03b4\u03b9\u1f70 \u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03ae\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5, \u0394\u03b9\u03b5\u03bc\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf \u03c4\u1f70 \u1f31\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b9\u03b1 \u03bc\u03bf\u03c5 \u1f11\u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u1fd6\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u1f10\u03c0\u1f76 \u03c4\u1f78\u03bd \u1f31\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u1f78\u03bd \u03bc\u03bf\u03c5 \u1f14\u03b2\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd \u03ba\u03bb\u1fc6\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd along with 0250, 037, 038, 1424, 1582, 124, 348, 788, 1279, 1579, and 517.\n\nAccording to [[Burnett Hillman Streeter|B. H. Streeter]], Codex Beratinus is a tertiary witness of the [[Caesarean text-type|Caesarean text]].<ref>B. H. Streeter, [http://www.katapi.org.uk/4Gospels/Ch4.htm ''The Four Gospels. A Study of Origins the Manuscripts Tradition, Sources, Authorship, & Dates''], MacMillan and Co Limited, Oxford 1924.</ref> It is grouped with [[Codex Petropolitanus Purpureus|N]], [[Sinope Gospels|O]], [[Rossano Gospels|\u03a3]], and [[Uncial 080]] to constitute the [[Purple parchment|Purple Uncials]]. [[Kurt Aland|Aland]] categorized the first four into [[Categories of New Testament manuscripts|Category V]],<ref name = Aland/> and it is certain that they are more Byzantine than anything else.<ref>[http://www.skypoint.com/members/waltzmn/ManuscriptsUncials.html#uPhi Codex Beratinus \u03a6 (043)]: at the ''Encyclopedia of Textual Criticism''</ref> Aland did not categorize Uncial 080.<ref name = Aland/>\n\n== History ==\nFormerly it was believed to have been at Patmos.<ref name = Kenyon/><ref>[[Pierre Batiffol]], ''Les manuscrits grecs de Berat d'Albanie et le Codex Purpureus \u03a6'', Paris 1886, p. 8</ref> According to Xhevat Lloshi it came from [[Ballsh]].<ref>Xhevat Lloshi, [https://books.google.com/books?id=9_gXTda0HS8C&pg=PA94&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Rreth ALFABETIT T\u00eb Shqipes''] (2008), p. 94</ref> It was held in Berat, Albania from 1356.<ref name = Gregory/> The text of the codex was published by [[Pierre Batiffol]] in 1887. \"During [[World War II]], Hitler learned of it and sought it out. Several monks and priests risked their lives to hide the manuscript.\"<ref>[http://www.csntm.org/Expedition/Albania2007 Albania Expedition] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090810101850/http://csntm.org/Expedition/Albania2007 |date=2009-08-10 }} at the [[Center for the Study of New Testament Manuscripts|CSNTM]]</ref> Since 1971, it has been preserved at the [[National Archives of Albania]] in Tirana.<ref name = Metzger/><ref name = INTF>{{Cite web |url=http://intf.uni-muenster.de/vmr/NTVMR/ListeHandschriften.php?ObjID=20043 |title=Liste Handschriften |publisher=Institute for New Testament Textual Research |accessdate=16 March 2013 |location=M\u00fcnster}}</ref>\n\n[[Oscar von Gebhardt]] designated it by [[siglum]] \u03a6, which is often used in critical editions.\n\n==Importance as Cultural Heritage==\nThe Codex Purpureus Beratinus was inscribed on the [[UNESCO]]\u2019s [[Memory of the World Register]] in 2005 in recognition of its historical significance. The two Beratinus codices preserved in Albania are very important for the global community and the development of ancient biblical, liturgical and hagiographical literature and are part of the \"[[Purple parchment|seven purple codices]]\", which were written over a period of 13 centuries, i.e. from the sixth to the eighteenth centuries. The other five \"purple codices\" are in [[Italy]] (two), [[France]] (one), [[England]] (one), and [[Greece]] (one).<ref name=mow>{{cite web |title= Codex Purpureus Beratinus |url= http://portal.unesco.org/ci/en/ev.php-URL_ID=23105&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html |date= 2008-05-16 |publisher= UNESCO Memory of the World Programme |accessdate= 2009-12-15 |archive-url= https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20151214214829/http://portal.unesco.org/ci/en/ev.php-URL_ID=23105&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html |archive-date= 2015-12-14 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Bible}}\n\n* [[List of New Testament uncials]]\n* [[Textual criticism]]\n* [[Purple parchment]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090807103638/http://www.csntm.org/Manuscript/View/GA_043 High res images] at the [[CSNTM]]\n* R. Waltz, [http://www.skypoint.com/members/waltzmn/ManuscriptsUncials.html#uPhi Codex Beratinus \u03a6 (043)], ''Encyclopedia of Textual Criticism''\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118132013/http://portal.unesco.org/ci/en/ev.php-URL_ID=15990&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html |date=January 18, 2008 |title=A Codex Purpureus Beratinus at the UNESCO website }}\n* [http://portal.unesco.org/ci/fr/ev.php-URL_ID=16086&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=-459.html Website of Unesco]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081228095148/http://www.shqiperia.com/fq/kat/kid/171.html Kodik\u00ebt e Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb (\u2019Alb\u00e1niai k\u00f3dexek\u2019)]\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{commons category|Codex Beratinus}}\n* Pierre Batiffol, [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k67401b.r=batiffol.langEN ''Evangeliorum codex Graecus purpureus Beratinus \u03a6''], in: ''[[M\u00e9langes de l'\u00c9cole fran\u00e7aise de Rome|M\u00e9langes d'arch\u00e9ologie et d'histoire, de l'\u00e9cole fran\u00e7aise de Rome]]'' 5 (Paris and Rome, 1882), pp.&nbsp;358\u2013376.\n* {{Cite book | author = Pierre Batiffol | authorlink = Pierre Batiffol | url = http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k96302s.r=batiffol.langEN | title = Les manuscrits grecs de Berat d'Albanie et le Codex Purpureus \u03a6 | location = Paris | year = 1886}}\n* {{Cite book | author = W. H. P. Hatch | title = The Principal Uncial Manuscripts of the New Testament | publisher = The University of Chicago Press | year = 1939 | location = Chicago| author-link = William Hatch }}\n* {{Cite journal | author = J. Koder | url = http://www.deepdyve.com/lp/de-gruyter/zur-wiederentdeckung-zweier-codices-beratini-w0dQG0MNib?autoClickRent=true | title = Zur Wiederentdeckung zweier Codices Beratini | journal =  Byzantinische Zeitschrift |volume=65 |issue=2 | year = 1972 | pages = 327\u2013328|doi = 10.1515/byzs.1972.65.2.327}}\n* Shaban Sinani, ''Kodik\u00ebt e Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb dhe 2000-vjetori i krisht\u00ebrimit'', in: \"Media\", 2000/6.\n\n[[Category:History of Berat]]\n[[Category:Greek New Testament uncials|Beratinus]]\n[[Category:Purple parchment]]\n[[Category:6th-century biblical manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Memory of the World Register]]\n[[Category:Gospel Books]]\n[[Category:6th-century illuminated manuscripts]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the similarly named manuscript|Codex Beratinus II}}\n{{New Testament manuscript infobox\n| form   = Uncial\n| number = '''043'''\n| image  = Page from the Codex Purpureus Beratinus.JPG\n| isize  = 220\n| caption= Left: Facsimile of Matthew 6:30b-7:2a Right: Page from Codex Beratinus\n| name   = Beratinus\n| sign   = \u03a6\n| text   = [[Gospel of Matthew]], [[Gospel of Mark]]\n| script = [[Greek language|Greek]]\n| date   = 6th-century\n| found  =\n| now at = [[National Archives of Albania]]\n| cite   = P. Batiffol, ''Evangeliorum codex Graecus purpureus Beratinus \u03a6'', (Paris and Rome, 1882)\n| size   = {{\u00d7|31|27|cm}}\n| type   = [[Byzantine text-type]]\n| cat    = V\n| hand   =\n| note   =\n}}\n\n'''Codex Purpureus Beratinus''' ({{lang-sq|Kodiku i Beratit, Kodiku i Purpurt i Beratit}}) designated by '''\u03a6''' or '''043''' (in the [[Biblical manuscript#Gregory-Aland|Gregory-Aland]] numbering), \u03b5 17 ([[Biblical manuscript#Von Soden|von Soden]]), is an [[uncial]] [[illuminated manuscript]] [[Gospel book]] written in [[Greek language|Greek]]. Dated [[Palaeography|palaeographically]] to the 6th-century, the [[manuscript]] is written in an uncial hand on [[Purple parchment|purple vellum]] with silver ink. The [[codex]] is preserved at the Albanian National Archives (Nr. 1) in [[Tirana]], [[Albania]].{{r|Aland}} It was formerly possessed by the [[Saint George|St. George]] Church in the town of [[Berat]], Albania, hence the 'Beratinus' appellation.\n\n== Description ==\nCodex Beratinus contains only the [[Gospel of Matthew]] and the [[Gospel of Mark]], with several considerable [[lacuna (manuscripts)|lacunae]] (Matthew 1:1-6:3, 7:26-8:7, 18:23-19:3, and Mark 14:62-end). The codex contains 190 extant parchment leaves measuring 31.4 \u00d7 26.8&nbsp;cm, or approximately the same size as those of [[Codex Alexandrinus]], and have two columns per page, but the letters are much larger.<ref name = Kenyon>[[Frederic G. Kenyon]], [https://archive.org/stream/handbooktotextua00kenyuoft#page/120/mode/2up ''Handbook to the Textual Criticism of the New Testament''], London2, 1912, p. 120.</ref> It is written with 17 lines per page,<ref name=Aland>{{Cite book\n | last = Aland\n | first = Kurt\n | authorlink = Kurt Aland\n | last2 = Aland\n | first2 = Barbara\n | authorlink2 = Barbara Aland\n | others = Erroll F. Rhodes (trans.)\n | title = The Text of the New Testament: An Introduction to the Critical Editions and to the Theory and Practice of Modern Textual Criticism\n | publisher = [[William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company]]\n | year = 1995\n | location = Grand Rapids\n | page = 118\n | url = \n | doi = \n | id = \n | isbn = 978-0-8028-4098-1}}</ref> 8-12 letters per line, in very regular letters, in silver ink.<ref name = Metzger>[[Bruce M. Metzger]], [[Bart D. Ehrman]], \"The Text of the New Testament: Its Transmission, Corruption and Restoration\", ''[[Oxford University Press]]'' (New York - Oxford, 2005), p. 84.</ref> The title and the first line in Mark are written in gold.<ref name = Gregory>{{Cite book | last = Gregory | first = Caspar Ren\u00e9 | authorlink = Caspar Ren\u00e9 Gregory | title = Textkritik des Neuen Testaments | publisher = J.C. Hinrichs\u2019sche Buchhandlung | year = 1900 | location = Leipzig | volume = 1 | page = 93 | url = https://archive.org/stream/textkritikdesne00greggoog#page/n105/mode/2up | isbn = }}</ref> The writing is continuous in full lines without [[stichometry]]. Quotations from the [[Old Testament]] are marked with an inverted comma (<).\n\nThe text is divided according to the {{lang|grc|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03b1}} (chapters) and according to the [[Eusebian Canons|Ammonian Sections]] (smaller than {{lang|grc|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03b1}}). On the left margin are inserted the numerals of the {{lang|grc|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03b1}} and above the pages are inserted the {{lang|grc|\u03c4\u03b9\u03c4\u03bb\u03bf\u03b9}} (titles) of the {{lang|grc|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03b1}}. The numerals of the Ammonian sections are given on the left margin, and a references to the Eusebian Canons were added by a later hand in the 8th century. A note in the manuscript states that the loss of the other two Gospels is due to \"the [[Franks]] of [[Champagne, France|Champagne]]\", i.e. some of the [[Crusades|Crusaders]], who may have seen it while at [[Patmos]], where it was believed formerly to have been.{{r|Kenyon}}\n\n== Text ==\nThe Greek text of the codex is generally of the [[Byzantine text-type]], but it contains the long [[Western text-type|Western]] addition after Matthew 20:28, occurring also in [[Codex Bezae]]:<ref name = Metzger/> Aland gave for it the following textual profile: 131<sup>1</sup>, 83<sup>1/2</sup>, 11<sup>2</sup>, 18<sup>s</sup>.<ref name = Aland/>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"But seek to increase from that which is small, and to become less from which is greater. When you enter into a house and are summoned to dine, do not sit down at the prominent places, lest perchance a man more honorable than you come in afterwards, and he who invited you come and say to you, \"Go down lower\"; and you shall be ashamed. But if you sit down in the inferior place, and one inferior to you come in, then he that invited you will say to you, \"Go up higher\"; and this will be advantageous for you.\"<ref>Bruce M. Metzger, Bart D. Ehrman, ''The Text of the New Testament: Its Transmission, Corruption and Restoration'', [[Oxford University Press]], 2005, p. 71.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn [[Matthew 21:9]], the following interpolation occurs, sharing affinity only with [[Curetonian Gospels|syr<sup>cur</sup>]]:<ref>[[Eberhard Nestle]], [[Erwin Nestle]], Barbara Aland and [[Kurt Aland]] (eds), ''[[Novum Testamentum Graece]]'', 26th edition, (Stuttgart: ''[[Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft]]'', 1991), p. 58. [NA26]</ref>\n<blockquote>\n\u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b5\u03be\u03b5\u03bb\u03b8\u03bf\u03bd \u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c5\u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03b9\u03bd \u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03c9 \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03b9 \u03c7\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b4\u03bf\u03be\u03b1\u03b6\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03b8\u03b5\u03bf\u03bd \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9 \u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c9\u03bd \u03b5\u03b9\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n''And many went out to meet him; all who were seeing [him] round about were rejoicing and glorifying God.''\n</blockquote>\n\nIn Matthew 27:9, in the phrase \u03b5\u03c0\u03bb\u03b7\u03c1\u03c9\u03b8\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c1\u03b7\u03b8\u03b5\u03bd \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1 \u0399\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03bc\u03b9\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03b7\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 (''fulfilled what was spoken by Jeremiah the prophet'') the word \u0399\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03bc\u03b9\u03bf\u03c5 ([[Jeremiah]]) is omitted, as in [[Minuscule 33]], [[Codex Vercellensis|a]], [[Codex Veronensis|b]], [[Syriac Sinaiticus|syr<sup>s</sup>]], [[Peshitta|syr<sup>p</sup>]], and [[Coptic versions of the Bible|cop<sup>bo</sup>]].<ref name = NA81>\u039d\u039126, p. 81</ref>\n\nIn Matthew 27:16 it has additional reading \u03bf\u03c2 \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c6\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bd \u03b7\u03bd \u03b2\u03b5\u03b2\u03bb\u03b7\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c6\u03c5\u03bb\u03b1\u03ba\u03b7\u03bd (''who for murder and insurrection had been thrown in prison'').<ref name = NA81/>\n\nIn Matthew 27:35, it includes \u1f35\u03bd\u03b1 \u03c0\u03bb\u03b7\u03c1\u03ce\u03b8\u03b7 \u03c4\u1f78 \u1fe4\u03b7\u03b8\u1f72\u03bd \u03b4\u03b9\u1f70 \u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03ae\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5, \u0394\u03b9\u03b5\u03bc\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf \u03c4\u1f70 \u1f31\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b9\u03b1 \u03bc\u03bf\u03c5 \u1f11\u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u1fd6\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u1f10\u03c0\u1f76 \u03c4\u1f78\u03bd \u1f31\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u1f78\u03bd \u03bc\u03bf\u03c5 \u1f14\u03b2\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd \u03ba\u03bb\u1fc6\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd along with 0250, 037, 038, 1424, 1582, 124, 348, 788, 1279, 1579, and 517.\n\nAccording to [[Burnett Hillman Streeter|B. H. Streeter]], Codex Beratinus is a tertiary witness of the [[Caesarean text-type|Caesarean text]].<ref>B. H. Streeter, [http://www.katapi.org.uk/4Gospels/Ch4.htm ''The Four Gospels. A Study of Origins the Manuscripts Tradition, Sources, Authorship, & Dates''], MacMillan and Co Limited, Oxford 1924.</ref> It is grouped with [[Codex Petropolitanus Purpureus|N]], [[Sinope Gospels|O]], [[Rossano Gospels|\u03a3]], and [[Uncial 080]] to constitute the [[Purple parchment|Purple Uncials]]. [[Kurt Aland|Aland]] categorized the first four into [[Categories of New Testament manuscripts|Category V]],<ref name = Aland/> and it is certain that they are more Byzantine than anything else.<ref>[http://www.skypoint.com/members/waltzmn/ManuscriptsUncials.html#uPhi Codex Beratinus \u03a6 (043)]: at the ''Encyclopedia of Textual Criticism''</ref> Aland did not categorize Uncial 080.<ref name = Aland/>\n\n== History ==\nFormerly it was believed to have been at Patmos.<ref name = Kenyon/><ref>[[Pierre Batiffol]], ''Les manuscrits grecs de Berat d'Albanie et le Codex Purpureus \u03a6'', Paris 1886, p. 8</ref> According to Xhevat Lloshi it came from [[Ballsh]].<ref>Xhevat Lloshi, [https://books.google.com/books?id=9_gXTda0HS8C&pg=PA94&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Rreth ALFABETIT T\u00eb Shqipes''] (2008), p. 94</ref> It was held in Berat, Albania from 1356.<ref name = Gregory/> The text of the codex was published by [[Pierre Batiffol]] in 1887. \"During [[World War II]], Hitler learned of it and sought it out. Several monks and priests risked their lives to hide the manuscript.\"<ref>[http://www.csntm.org/Expedition/Albania2007 Albania Expedition] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090810101850/http://csntm.org/Expedition/Albania2007 |date=2009-08-10 }} at the [[Center for the Study of New Testament Manuscripts|CSNTM]]</ref> Since 1971, it has been preserved at the [[National Archives of Albania]] in Tirana.<ref name = Metzger/><ref name = INTF>{{Cite web |url=http://intf.uni-muenster.de/vmr/NTVMR/ListeHandschriften.php?ObjID=20043 |title=Liste Handschriften |publisher=Institute for New Testament Textual Research |accessdate=16 March 2013 |location=M\u00fcnster}}</ref>\n\n[[Oscar von Gebhardt]] designated it by [[siglum]] \u03a6, which is often used in critical editions.\n\n==Importance as Cultural Heritage==\nThe Codex Purpureus Beratinus was inscribed on the [[UNESCO]]\u2019s [[Memory of the World Register]] in 2005 in recognition of its historical significance. The two Beratinus codices preserved in Albania are very important for the global community and the development of ancient biblical, liturgical and hagiographical literature and are part of the \"[[Purple parchment|seven purple codices]]\", which were written over a period of 13 centuries, i.e. from the sixth to the eighteenth centuries. The other five \"purple codices\" are in [[Italy]] (two), [[France]] (one), [[England]] (one), and [[Greece]] (one).<ref name=mow>{{cite web |title= Codex Purpureus Beratinus |url= http://portal.unesco.org/ci/en/ev.php-URL_ID=23105&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html |date= 2008-05-16 |publisher= UNESCO Memory of the World Programme |accessdate= 2009-12-15 |archive-url= https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20151214214829/http://portal.unesco.org/ci/en/ev.php-URL_ID=23105&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html |archive-date= 2015-12-14 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Bible}}\n\n* [[List of New Testament uncials]]\n* [[Textual criticism]]\n* [[Purple parchment]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090807103638/http://www.csntm.org/Manuscript/View/GA_043 High res images] at the [[CSNTM]]\n* R. Waltz, [http://www.skypoint.com/members/waltzmn/ManuscriptsUncials.html#uPhi Codex Beratinus \u03a6 (043)], ''Encyclopedia of Textual Criticism''\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118132013/http://portal.unesco.org/ci/en/ev.php-URL_ID=15990&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html |date=January 18, 2008 |title=A Codex Purpureus Beratinus at the UNESCO website }}\n* [http://portal.unesco.org/ci/fr/ev.php-URL_ID=16086&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=-459.html Website of Unesco]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081228095148/http://www.shqiperia.com/fq/kat/kid/171.html Kodik\u00ebt e Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb (\u2019Alb\u00e1niai k\u00f3dexek\u2019)]\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{commons category|Codex Beratinus}}\n* Pierre Batiffol, [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k67401b.r=batiffol.langEN ''Evangeliorum codex Graecus purpureus Beratinus \u03a6''], in: ''[[M\u00e9langes de l'\u00c9cole fran\u00e7aise de Rome|M\u00e9langes d'arch\u00e9ologie et d'histoire, de l'\u00e9cole fran\u00e7aise de Rome]]'' 5 (Paris and Rome, 1882), pp.&nbsp;358\u2013376.\n* {{Cite book | author = Pierre Batiffol | authorlink = Pierre Batiffol | url = http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k96302s.r=batiffol.langEN | title = Les manuscrits grecs de Berat d'Albanie et le Codex Purpureus \u03a6 | location = Paris | year = 1886}}\n* {{Cite book | author = W. H. P. Hatch | title = The Principal Uncial Manuscripts of the New Testament | publisher = The University of Chicago Press | year = 1939 | location = Chicago| author-link = William Hatch }}\n* {{Cite journal | author = J. Koder | url = http://www.deepdyve.com/lp/de-gruyter/zur-wiederentdeckung-zweier-codices-beratini-w0dQG0MNib?autoClickRent=true | title = Zur Wiederentdeckung zweier Codices Beratini | journal =  Byzantinische Zeitschrift |volume=65 |issue=2 | year = 1972 | pages = 327\u2013328|doi = 10.1515/byzs.1972.65.2.327}}\n* Shaban Sinani, ''Kodik\u00ebt e Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb dhe 2000-vjetori i krisht\u00ebrimit'', in: \"Media\", 2000/6.\n\n[[Category:History of Berat]]\n[[Category:Greek New Testament uncials|Beratinus]]\n[[Category:Purple parchment]]\n[[Category:6th-century biblical manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Memory of the World Register]]\n[[Category:Gospel Books]]\n[[Category:6th-century illuminated manuscripts]]\n", "name_user": "79.106.126.241", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eText)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Codex_Beratinus"}
